snippet.textDisplay: People act like "load management" means players are lazily taking a vacation. First of all, it's not done by the players; the players mostly want to play every single game. The team's management makes the decisions. Secondly, there's a REASON teams have 14-15 on the roster and dress out 12-13 on a given night. By definition, someone is going to be getting those minutes, and someone else isn't. Who sits? That decision belongs to management. Fans act like when they choose to watch a team with 15 players it's up to them which 8 or 9 get playing time, but that's not how it's going to work. And third, management is informed by really precise data about players' motions, the sort of things that indicate when there is a higher likelihood of injury. When the science says it's time to rest, management follows the science. And fourth: when a fan's favorite player is sitting, that player's replacement is cordially invited to play BETTER and make the fans still feel happy they were there that night. EVERY player in the NBA is a top 600 player in the whole freaking world (there are about 450 NBA players in the NBA, but let's admit that some players in Europe and Asia are better than SOME NBA players). If a bench player gets a chance because LeBron or Kawhi or whoever is being load managed, then that player should man up and PERFORM. And fifth, load management lets bench players develop. What is a playoffs team supposed to do in May if a star goes down and the bench players haven't had a chance in December and January to get serious minutes? May is not the time to learn how to play. Bench players need big minutes during the regular season if they're going to develop.

snippet.textDisplay: Max is confused. The Warriors didn't lose the 2016 championship because they chased 73 wins; Curry's injury was the most important one, and it was just a freak thing, not a result of too many minutes. He landed funny for his first injury vs. Houston, and slipped on water for his second one. And Bogut's injury was important, but he got PLENTY of rest during the 73-win season; he wasn't over-worked in pursuit of 73 wins.  Curry and Bogut resting a few more games during the regular season wouldn't have prevented their injuries. Those injuries were just part of the game, the sort of thing that happens sometimes. And let's face it: over the past 4 decades, in at least half of the seasons the playoffs have been significantly impacted by SOMEONE getting injured.
